Gordon Paynter wrote:
&gt; Hi all:
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;m a relative newcomer to the Heritrix software. I have a couple of 
&gt; question about Heritrix&#39; handling of HTML forms which I have been unable 
&gt; to answer through the manuals or Javadocs. (I haven&#39;t looked at the 
&gt; code.. yet)  I&#39;m using version 1.4.0.
&gt; 
&gt; I assume from the behaviour I see that Heritrix will attempt to crawl 
&gt; &quot;through&quot; HTML forms. I assume it does this in extractorHTML class, and 
&gt; simply &quot;submits&quot; the forms without supplying any values.  Can anyone 
&gt; confirm (or deny) this?

This is correct - if the URI can be found in the action-field it will be 
ancountered as a new seed (without parameters)

&gt; 
&gt; It appears (in my case) that it does this even when the form has the 
&gt; attribute
&gt; 
&gt;    method=&quot;post&quot;
&gt; 
&gt; indicating an HTTP POST instead of an HTTP GET. Again, Can anyone 
&gt; confirm or deny?

Yes - even action=&quot;POST&quot; will be new seeds - and tried through HTTP-get

&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; In practice, the problem I am seeing is really the fault of the Web 
&gt; site: it uses a relative URL as the &quot;action&quot; for the form, and re-uses 
&gt; the same form on several different pages, thus generating a range of 
&gt; invalid URLs, but the nature of the site is to quietly accept these bad 
&gt; URLs... what a mess.  Here&#39;s an example URL if anyone is interested:
&gt; 
&gt;   http://blog.greens.org.nz/index.php/2005/06/28/
&gt; 
&gt; the &quot;Subscribe&quot; button mid-way down the right-hand column effectively 
&gt; takes you back to the homepage with a mangled, but valid, URL.
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; However, I&#39;m curious (and a little concerned) about the HTML form 
&gt; behaviour noted above. Any advice on these issues would be appreciated.

We have made a simple subclass of ExtractorHTML to deal with this 
problem. It does not try to extract links from tags named &quot;form&quot; at all 
- another variant would try to look for &quot;POST&quot; - this has not been 
implemented yet.
We use this extractor instead of the default one on problematic sites.

If you want the code mail me back - I will send it to you directly

